# TypeScript Rules

## Type Safety First
- Keep code compatible with strict TypeScript settings in `tsconfig.json`.
- Avoid `any`; use `unknown`, generics, discriminated unions, and type guards.
- Use type assertions only when runtime constraints guarantee correctness.
- Prefer `readonly` for immutable domain models and config objects.

## Type Modeling
- Use `type` and `interface` based on readability and use case; do not force one globally.
- Use `type` for unions, intersections, mapped/conditional types.
- Use `interface` for extendable object contracts and public object APIs.
- Keep component prop names explicit and suffixed with `Props` when exported.

## Type Placement
- Keep local types close to their usage site.
- Promote shared contracts to `src/types` only when reused across features.
- Keep API DTO types near `features/*/data`; keep business entities near `features/*/domain`.
- Prefer explicit exported types for module public APIs.

## Imports And Exports
- Prefer `import type` for type-only imports.
- Keep imports stable and avoid deep imports into another feature internals.
- Expose cross-feature types through explicit public entry points.

## Functions And Errors
- Add explicit return types for exported functions and complex hooks.
- Prefer small pure functions for `domain` logic.
- Prefer `async/await` and handle rejected promises at call boundaries.
- Use typed error normalization in `data` and surface UI-safe errors to hooks/components.